From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000003 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: kenton-response contributor <noreply@example.com>
Date: Tue, 22 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Cage-compatible shared ReadOnlyHeap via memfd + MAP_FIXED

Today V8 only enables SoleReadOnlyHeap when
`v8_enable_pointer_compression_shared_cage` is on. Embedders that use
isolated cages for tenant separation (cloudflare/workerd) cannot share
the read-only snapshot across isolates and pay ~10 KB of duplicated
RO heap per isolate × N tenants.

This patch lifts that restriction by introducing a process-wide
read-only slab backed by a `memfd_create()` file (Linux), mapped at
identical intra-cage offsets in every cage via `MAP_FIXED |
MAP_SHARED | PROT_READ`. Because cages are 4 GB aligned, a 32-bit
compressed pointer `V` decodes to `cage_base + V` regardless of cage,
and that physical address is the same set of pages in every cage's
virtual mapping.

The compressed-pointer decode path is **unchanged** — no indirection,
no extra branch on the hot path. The only V8 changes are:

1. `src/heap/shared-ro-slab.{h,cc}` — new files holding the process-
   wide memfd and per-cage attach helpers.
2. `src/init/isolate-allocator.cc` — call `SharedRoSlab::AttachCage()`
   immediately after the cage's 4 GB virtual reservation succeeds.
3. `src/heap/read-only-heap.{h,cc}` — when the slab is active,
   `IsReadOnlySpaceShared()` returns true and the SoleReadOnlyHeap
   path is taken even with isolated cages.
4. `src/flags/flag-definitions.h` — new flag
   `--shared_ro_heap_via_memfd` (off by default; embedders opt in).
5. `BUILD.gn` + bazel — add the new files to the build graph.

A standalone Linux prototype validating the data-structure and
read-only enforcement is at
`kenton-response/src/solution/cage-compatible-ro/cross_cage_shared_ro_proto.cc`.
That program creates 8 cages and verifies every cage decodes
compressed pointer 0x40 to the same physical bytes (8/8 OK), writes
SIGSEGV (8/8 OK), and PSS only grows by 160 KB instead of 8 × 64 KB.

Tested:
- Linux x86_64: prototype ran inside the kenton-bench Docker image,
  result PROTOTYPE VERIFIED, full output in commit log.
- macOS / Windows: not yet — Phase A is Linux-first; macOS uses
  shm_open + mmap and Windows uses CreateFileMapping +
  MapViewOfFileEx, both behind separate follow-up patches.
- mjsunit: TODO — pending compile of patched V8.
- octane / speedometer: TODO — same.

Memory savings (kenton-response/results/SUMMARY.md, V8 12.8, 3-run
median, R²=1.000 linear regression across 1..1000 isolates):
- stage_0 used-heap per isolate: 10.4 KB → shareable.
- At 1000 workerd-style isolates: ~10 MB RSS saved per process.
- Ratio of stage_0 / stage_3 (full handler-run heap): ~10.8% — the
  measured upper bound on "Phase A only" savings. Larger savings
  require Phase 2 (shared context template, shared heap region pool).

